body: Dropped Katherine off at the old Museum. She’s going on a music camp at Coolum
We buy water and soft drink for later
We drive to the first EV charger. It’s occupied by someone who has no plans to return to their car, so we give up and proceed to the next.
We visit a Mater Prize Home. Looks like a great place to live, but the swimming pool ruins the back yard.
We investigate the new Tesla Superchargers at the shopping centre, Runaway Bay. It’s popular - there was only one bay left!
We stop at the gas station to buy some dinner
Appointment with Colorectal surgeon
Waiting for Katherine to arrive. She caught the bus from Griffith University after her Japanese lesson.
Frozen pasta dinners for Katherine, and lemon cakes for me.
Jake and I both parked our Teslas side-by-side on level 8 of the carpark. He said that the Mercedes would normally park there, so I checked my sentry video and found who the driver was.
We weren’t at home long enough to register as a location it seems.
We ordered dinner from Red Rooster. I had a Reds dinner box. It probably wasn’t the ideal choice as I think it causes me some problems later.
Took pictures of some waterlilies in the lagoon.
We had coffee and then Anita bought an expensive short-peaked cap from a nearby sports store.
I was wondering up until this point why I was carrying a heavy camera. Fortunately it got better from coming across the goanna. There was also the hairy caterpillars just before.
There were two butcher birds hanging around the picnic area looking for scraps that made excellent subjects.
Dropped Katherine off at the bus stop

I remove the stains that are affecting the paint of the WRX. It’s coming from insects, or maybe possums, or trees? Whatever the source, they are really difficult to remove. I’m using a preparation that’s for removing calcium deposits on car windows and contains sulphuric acid!

It takes hours, so I decide to use the car cover to prevent more over the rest of the weekend.
Picking up Katherine. She was at a cat and dog show at the convention centre
I arranged to do an evening shift to be there to show the new Solutions Architect a working sleep laboratory.
They ran out of meatballs. He said they make more after 7:00pm.
There were things to do today, so we did the shorter walk to the park and back. We didn’t even stop for coffee at MacDonalds to save time.
I dropped Anita off near the shopping centre. She was going to a catchup morning tea with former work colleagues.
Parked nearby and walked to the church
This was the most convenient place for us all to vote in the council elections.
Back to the car. Anita decided to walk home as she was feeling a bit nauseous.
I bought an ozeto impact drill to replace the WRX door latches. Katherine wanted to buy some ribbon from Spotlight, so that’s why I’m at a different Bunnings store
Dropped Katherine off at a school friends place. They are playing Dungeons and Dragons
We bought two ham, cheese and tomato sandwiches and a steak pie for Anita.

I installed the replacement top dash assembly in the WRX. The old one was much harder to remove than I thought. One of the clips ended up breaking to get it out.

I decided to also replace the bottom windscreen strip. Unfortunately the clip holding everything broke when removing the assembly around the windscreen wipers.
Bought some automotive fasteners and a proper impact driver before they closed.
I thought I had forgotten my ID badge so went back home to look for it. It was attached to my backpack, so I had it in the car the whole time!
A longer morning walk
Breakfast at Maccas
Haircut to look more presentable at the Japanese Governor-Generals reception
I booked an Uber for the trip to the Japanese Governor-Generals reception at Hamilton. It was a black Tesla Model Y
A very interesting evening. I learnt a few things about early Japanese migration to Australia and the food was awesome! (I suffered a bit for it later, but this time it was worth it)
Another Uber to get to Katherine’s QYO Concert at the old museum. This time it was a BYD Atto 3 driven by an Indian man wearing a turban.

Great concert by both wind orchestras. They played very difficult pieces from a wide range of composers.

Katherine had some of the first horn parts this time.
Stopped to have breakfast. The QESH charger wasn’t occupied so I charged back up to 80% while we waited for our breakfast order.

The botanical gardens are nearby, so we visit and go for a walk around the lagoon. Anita is wearing her open shoes and I’m wearing my new shoes, so we couldn’t get too adventurous. The ground was very waterlogged.

We have a look at the Endeavour Prize Home. It’s a renovation of an existing property. The layout is a little unusual, especially the master bedroom.

The property includes a huge four bay shed which had a car hoist installed. The main problem for me was the large gravel area around the garage spoiling the look of the backyard. Also the views from the house a spoiled by the garage.
We drive to the second prize home on the list, but discover that it’s not for viewing.

Had lunch at Twin Waters Resort. I had a toasted ham and cheese croissant. It was too much to eat, after such a big breakfast.

We didn’t do any walking around the lagoon. Anita said that was just for the residents.
We needed a toilet stop, so picked the  MacDonalds at Coochin Creek. There were two polestars charging at the Evie DC chargers nearby.

We were interested in going to the top of Wild Horse Mountain so went to investigate. I think I’d been up there several years ago. As it turned out it was a good thing I’d forgotten how steep the climb was up the closed access road.
The walk down was a lot easier. There were a surprising number of mushrooms at the base of the trees. Maybe they’ve always been there. I wouldn’t have been looking before
We drove straight home with no more stops. The Tesla is awesome for trips like this.

Tried to buy the Bluetooth Hub for the switch I bought last week and it’s not anywhere!

I visited the camping section and bought a 20 watt solar panel system. That’s almost enough to recharge an iPad if there’s enough sun. I’m hoping I can strap it to the top of the Burley Trailer.
I stopped at the pharmacy to buy some Metamucil. And sandwiches at the bakery.
Picking up our shopping. We don’t go to the supermarket any more for most of our supplies.
There are some specific items that aren’t available from Woolworths eg Italian pasta meals
Refuelled the WRX. It’s always a special trip these days.
I bought almost 10 litres of mower fuel. The recommendation on Google is standard 91 RON. It cost me almost $20.00
Worked an evening shift because Sean is away at the TSANZ conference at the Gold Coast
I got there late expecting Chloe to be there, but there was no one. Chloe finally arrived at almost 9:30am. It’s a good thing most of the doctors were away.
Came home early because I was suffering from mild vertigo.
Anita had an Optus check to deposit.
Bought some TV dinners
When Katherine arrived I went to Coles to get some more socks
We are really waiting nearby next to the pool
Katherine’s university fees have come due, so I transfer $3000.00 to Anita’s account. The total bill for half the year is $4000.00
The creek is up; proof of a lot of recent rain.
Lots of midges flying in clouds along the path. Bin chickens grazing in the field under the power lines and there was even a wallaby there too.
Breakfast

Installed the drivers window trim. The original piece took five minutes to remove, but the new trim piece took a few hours! That had a lot to do with needing to remove the rear vision mirror.

In the process, the threads were damaged, so I got out the huge tap and die set and cleaned up the bolt threads for the mirror. I ended up having to also clean up the holes as well. That effort made a huge difference, and the bolts went in easily now.
Drive around the local streets to test the window. There was some noises and groans coming from the door that weren’t there before!
The next thing to replace was the driver door striker. My theory was that the old striker was allowing the door to move around a little and making the noises.

I tried to use the impact driver I bought at Supercheap, but it didn’t do anything. I couldn’t figure out how it worked anyway. Fortunately, the impact drill I also purchased at Bunnings worked surprisingly well and easily removed the bolts! I even had an adaptor to fit the huge Phillips head that came with the impact driver to do it.
To make things really difficult, I ran out of daylight and then it started to rain heavily so I had to move all the tools and wait.

Went for a longer test drive. The new striker made it a bit harder to close the door, but it totally fixed the groaning noises from the door. It also eliminated the wind noises at highway speeds! Fantastic!
Anita received the news that Eli had passed away. We discussed what we will do assuming the funeral will be up at Harvey Bay.

We checked out the newly opened coffee shop. I also ordered breakfast as well. The coffee is cold brewed, but was a little bitter to my tastes. I prefer a milder blend. Also I didn’t get any butter for my toast, and there was no salt available. Even though sugar was available at the table, most of the ‘sugar’ was really artificial sweetener.
It must have been an ambo’s birthday because there were three ambulances at the coffee shop just before we arrived.
Charged the car to 90% in preparation for a day trip to Toowoomba.
Cleaned all the big splatters off the windscreen. I parked away from the petrol pumps as it would have looked strange for a Tesla to be parked at a pump!
Lots of different mushrooms around this time!
